<DOC><DOCNO> AP890909-0134 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 2116EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-StormDeaths     09-09 0249</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Storm Deaths,0258</SECOND><HEAD>Two Boys Drown in Kansas City; Indiana Woman Struck by Lightning</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Two Missouri teen-agers drowned in separate incidents whileplaying in flood-swollen waters, and at least seven people wereinjured in Indiana, one by lightning, as a powerful thunderstormmoved through Saturday.   Bryan Hammer, 18, of Gladstone, Mo., was killed when he waspulled into the 7-feet-deep Line Creek in Kansas City, Mo.,authorities said.   Hammer's roommate, Mike Marquez, said the two had gone to thecreek about midnight.   ``We were out late and had nothing else to do, so we thought we'dmess around in the water,'' Marquez said.   Up to 4 inches of rain fell in the Kansas City area overnight.   A 13-year-old North Kansas City boy died when he was swept into astorm drain Friday night. Robert Ragsdale was pronounced dead about7 p.m. at North Kansas City Hospital.   Ragsdale and a friend ``were riding the drainage ditch like awater slide and the water current just got too strong,'' said BobJones, a spokesman for the Kansas City Police Department.   In Indiana, the storm sparked flash flooding and cut electricalpower in Indianapolis.   An unidentified 14-year-old girl was treated and released afterlightning struck near her during halftime of Saturday's footballgame between Miami of Ohio and Purdue in Lafayette, officials said.   And in New Palestine, between six and eight people received minorinjuries when gusting winds knocked down a tent at a festival,police said.</TEXT></DOC>